<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: CNES-88 / Famido / Famicube]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12475&amp;p=143142#p143142"><![CDATA[
Yeah, &quot;byte&quot; and &quot;word&quot; both are a function of the specific architecture being used.<br /><br />Using a power of 2 for the word size gets you certain nice things for the roll / shift operators, but it's not insurmountable for other word sizes. Other human languages sometimes use the term &quot;octets&quot; to make this difference explicit.<br /><br />6 bits is enough to contain all-uppercase english text, and a 12-bit machine could hold three BCD digits or two bytes in a single word. Forever ago, when memory was measured in the range of &quot;dollar per bit&quot; to even &quot;dollar per kilobit&quot;, this kind of optimization made sense.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3512">lidnariq</a> — Sun Mar 15, 2015 9:01 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
