<author><name><![CDATA[koitsu]]></name></author>
<updated>2015-03-15T20:48:15-07:00</updated>
<published>2015-03-15T20:48:15-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12475&amp;p=143140#p143140</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12475&amp;p=143140#p143140"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: CNES-88 / Famido / Famicube]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12475&amp;p=143140#p143140"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Espozo wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />So &quot;byte&quot; doesn't isn't really a concrete term, just like &quot;word&quot;? I thought byte had to equal 8. Again, is there a reason why 8 was the common number? I'm surprised it wasn't 10, because you can get the number 1024 with all 10 bits, and 1024 translates a lot better to the base 10 system than 256.<br /></div><br />The term &quot;byte&quot; has referred to 8 bits since the early 1960s via IBM's introduction of EBCDIC, so anyone talking about this is just sharing some history with you (good to know your roots).  But yes, there are some &quot;archaic&quot; systems that use 6 bits and 7 bits for a byte.  Don't get hung up on this though.<br /><br />You might also hear the term &quot;octet&quot;, which is more appropriate in some ways as it specifically refers to 8 bits.  The most common use of the term &quot;octet&quot; these days (in my experience) is when referring to part of an IPv4 address (192.168.1.50; 1st octet = 192, 2nd octet = 168, ...).<br /><br />By now you should be able to guess at the reason a byte is 8 bits rather than 10 (hint: like most &quot;historic things&quot;, it has to do with cost).  <a href="http://programmers.stackexchange.com/questions/120126/what-is-the-history-of-why-bytes-are-eight-bits" class="postlink">You can read this stackexchange.com post</a> (please be sure to read the comments, not just what got voted up) for further details.<br /><br />The term &quot;word&quot; is significantly more vague, because it varies per architecture (and/or CPU mode) you're in.  Because of the era I grew up in and what processors I learned (particularly 65816), the term &quot;word&quot; to me always means 16 bits, and for quite some time that was the norm (especially considering Intel's introduction of mnemonics like DWORD PTR (32-bit) and QWORD PTR (64-bit)).  But on some architectures, &quot;word&quot; could mean 64-bit (like it does on the x64).  Wikipedia has a chart of what architectures define what size as a &quot;word&quot;.<br /><br />Your logic about &quot;easy to get to 1024 with 10 bits because 1024 is better to the base 10 system&quot; <a href="http://begthequestion.info/" class="postlink">begs the question</a>.  I don't see any relation between that and the base 10 system.  I hope this isn't going <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hard_disk_drive#Units" class="postlink">the Route of Stupid</a> (<a href="http://www.bit-tech.net/news/bits/2007/10/26/seagate_lawsuit_concludes_settlement_announced/1" class="postlink">reference</a>).<br /><br />Maybe you're starting to think of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary-coded_decimal" class="postlink">BCD</a>?  Without getting into the hairy details (Wikipedia is full of sperglords), the commonplace use of BCD is for &quot;human decimal numbers&quot;.  The easiest way to explain it is like this, referring to incrementing numbers or how numbers are calculated:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Normal/non-BCD      BCD<br />...<br />$07 (%00000111)     $07 (%00000111)<br />$08 (%00001000)     $08 (%00001000)<br />$09 (%00001001)     $09 (%00001001)<br />$0A (%00001010)     $10 (%00010000)<br />$0B (%00001011)     $11 (%00010001)<br />...<br /></div><br />And before you ask: yes, most 65xxx series CPUs support BCD (that's what the D bit in P is for), except the NES's Ricoh-made 6502 CPU, which lacks BCD support.  The SNES supports it fine.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3">koitsu</a> — Sun Mar 15, 2015 8:48 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
