<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2015-03-15T12:52:59-07:00</updated>
<published>2015-03-15T12:52:59-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12475&amp;p=143110#p143110</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12475&amp;p=143110#p143110"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: CNES-88 / Famido / Famicube]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12475&amp;p=143110#p143110"><![CDATA[
Since when does the Jaguar have twin 68Ks? I was told it had three processors:<br /><ul><li>MC68000, responsible for booting the system and some I/O tasks </li><li>Tom: A 32-bit RISC CPU and a 64-bit fixed-function GPU </li><li>Jerry: The same RISC CPU, with a few more digital signal processing instructions, and a pair of 16-bit DACs </li></ul>Some games would run most of the game on the Tom CPU and used the 68K mostly to read the controllers. Other games, especially games whose programmers had come from Genesis or Amiga, ran the game logic on the 68K and used the Tom CPU mostly to build display lists for the GPU. But Tom does have a 64-bit data bus to the RAM, which was enough to make the Jaguar &quot;64-bit&quot; at the time.<br /><br />AMD would later reuse the Jaguar name for the fully 64-bit combination CPU/GPU in the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One consoles.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sun Mar 15, 2015 12:52 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
